Your code has the basic idea, but there are a few modifications to make in order to get it working correctly.

1. You should use braces `{}` to group multiple statements together for clarity and correctness, especially in the `if-else` conditions.
2. The loop you&#39;ve written assumes that the value of `A` will increment automatically. In a real-world scenario, you&#39;d likely need to update `A` by reading a new value from the device each iteration.
3. The variable `control` needs to be defined outside of the loop. If you define it inside the loop, it&#39;ll be re-initialized to 0 on every iteration, which isn&#39;t what you want.

Here&#39;s a corrected version of your code:

```java
int A = ValueToReciveDeviceEveryTime;  // Assuming this value is fetched somehow
int A_old = A;
boolean B = false;   
int control = 0;

// I&#39;ve assumed you want to loop until an alarm is triggered. Adjust as needed.
while (B == false) { 
    if(A_old == A) {
        control++;
    } else {
        control = 0;
    }

    if (control == 3) {
        B = true;  // alarm condition
    } else {
        A_old = A;
    }

    A = getNewValueFromDevice();  // You&#39;ll need to implement this or something similar to update the value of A
}
```

You&#39;ll need to replace `getNewValueFromDevice()` with however you&#39;re reading the new value for `A` from the device. 

This program will continue to loop until `B` becomes `true`, i.e., until the alarm condition is met. If you want to loop for a set number of iterations (like 32000 in your original code), you can replace the `while` loop with a `for` loop and check the value of `B` within the loop to break out early if needed.

