You are right. `@LoadBalanced` should integrate with `DiscoveryClient` behind the scene such that you do not need to deal with it. 

Behind the scene `LoadBalancerAutoConfiguration` will process the `@LoadBalanced` annotated `RestTemplate` to setup such integration. But it will only enabled if there are any `LoadBalancerClient` implementation in the class-path. So guess that you forget to add any load-balancer implementation to the class-path ? 

You should add `spring-cloud-starter-loadbalancer` to your project , quoted from [this][1] as follows : 
&gt; Important : To use a load-balanced RestTemplate, you need to have a load-balancer implementation in your classpath. Add Spring Cloud LoadBalancer starter to your project in order to use it.


Another reason is if you define multiple `RestTemplate` beans , you have to use the `@LoadBalanced` which is also a `@Qualifier` to inject the one with the load balancing feature : 

``` java
@Service
public class PlanetService {

    @Autowired
    @LoadBalanced
    private RestTemplate restTemplate;

}

```

And one more reason is hostname does not allow underscores.(see [this][2]). So you should change the name of the service that you call  (i.e `planet_ms`) to another name without underscores. 


  [1]: https://docs.spring.io/spring-cloud-commons/docs/current/reference/html/#rest-template-loadbalancer-client
  [2]: https://stackoverflow.com/a/60239197/339637

I accidentally discovered a fix to the problem. Let me group things into ones that don&#39;t matter and the ones that do

### Things that don&#39;t matter

1. Putting a `@LoadBalanced` annotation on a field/parameter of type `RestTemplate` if you only have one bean of that type (like I did)
```java
    public PlanetService(/* you don&#39;t need @LoadBalanced here, but you can put it if you want */ RestTemplate restTemplate) {
        this.restTemplate = restTemplate;
    }
```
2. Having an explicit `loadbalancer` dependency (Eureka got it covered, look at the Compile Dependencies section [here][1])
```xml
&lt;!-- you don&#39;t need it --&gt;

&lt;!--        &lt;dependency&gt;--&gt;
&lt;!--            &lt;groupId&gt;org.springframework.cloud&lt;/groupId&gt;--&gt;
&lt;!--            &lt;artifactId&gt;spring-cloud-starter-loadbalancer&lt;/artifactId&gt;--&gt;
&lt;!--            &lt;version&gt;4.0.4&lt;/version&gt;--&gt;
&lt;!--        &lt;/dependency&gt;--&gt;
```
### Things that do matter

1. Avoiding low dashes. I was under the impression that URI standards don&#39;t apply to application names since they should be replaced with valid host-port pairs anyway, but no. `planet-ms` is fine, `planet_ms` is not
```
{
  &quot;error_message&quot;: &quot;Request URI does not contain a valid hostname: http://planet_ms/api/planets?name=hoth&quot;
}
```
2. *(it&#39;s the fix I was referring to at the beginning!)* Choosing a method of making requests to your microservices and sticking with it. See, I used the `@LoadBalanced` annotation to communicate with one microservice (`planet-ms`) and `DiscoveryClient` to communicate with another one (`converter-ms`). Like so:
```java
@Service
@RequiredArgsConstructor
public class WeightService {
    private final RestTemplate restTemplate;
    private final MicroserviceUtil mu;
    public Double getWeightInKilos(String weight) {
        String[] weightAndUnit = weight.split(&quot;(?&lt;=\\d)(?=[a-z]+)&quot;);
        Double value = Double.valueOf(weightAndUnit[0]);
        String unit = weightAndUnit[1];
        if (unit.equals(WeightUnit.KILOS.toString())) {
            return value;
        } else if (unit.equals(WeightUnit.POUNDS.toString())) {
            return restTemplate.getForObject(String.format(&quot;http://%s/api/kilos?pounds=%s&quot;,
                    mu.getHostAndPort(&quot;converter-ms&quot;), value), Double.class);
        }
        throw new IllegalArgumentException(&quot;Unsupported unit&quot;);
    }
}
```
```java
@Component
@RequiredArgsConstructor
public class MicroserviceUtil {
    private final DiscoveryClient discoveryClient;
    public String getHostAndPort(String microserviceName) {
        var converterMicroservice = discoveryClient.getInstances(microserviceName).get(0); // no balancing needed since I have only one instance per microservice
        return converterMicroservice.getHost() + &quot;:&quot; + converterMicroservice.getPort();
    }
}
```
It led to this:
```
WARN 2580 --- [nio-8080-exec-1] o.s.c.l.core.RoundRobinLoadBalancer      : No servers available for service: host.docker.internal
```
If I replace this
```java
            return restTemplate.getForObject(String.format(&quot;http://%s/api/kilos?pounds=%s&quot;,
                    mu.getHostAndPort(&quot;converter-ms&quot;), value), Double.class);
```
with this
```java
            return restTemplate.getForObject(&quot;http://converter-ms/api/kilos?pounds=&quot; + value,
                    Double.class);
```
everything works fine

